    description_en:
      '"Truths that can only appear opaque,\nand yet, the things that are still seen."\n\nFor humans alive in this world, the afterlife — including purgatory — is a future world, and everything in that coming future can only be opaque in form. Even at the moment that future arrives as the present, humans can perceive only fragments of that present; perceiving the truth in its full transparency is not easy. To grasp only a sliver of an event in reality and yet to take that sliver as the whole — this is as ordinary as everyday human life.\nSIM_Moby\'s awakening to "a single life. a single death" is no different. The order of life and death is opaque and abstract, and the philosophy the artist has glimpsed within it may be only a tiny part of some vast nature.\n \nIf so, then the seemingly absolute providence of life and death — which might be read as pessimistic — must also have an optimistic hope on its other face. To be opaque is to say that, while not sharply visible, that abstract something is nonetheless clearly there. We may not understand everything, and yet — is there not a hope, certain and visible, that allows us to perceive and to step forward?\n \n"The Visibility of Purgatory"\n \nFollowing the previous collage series <SIM_Opacity: The Opacity of Purgatory>, this series is built from an upper part that expresses opacity and a lower part of abstraction that expresses visibility.\n \nThe upper part is made by printing existing flat digital paintings on various materials, collaging them onto canvas, then adding pointillist acrylic dots and finally affixing acrylic sticks one by one. Through this, the viewer experiences shifts in the color of the collage and paint as the acrylic rods refract the light.\n \nThe lower part is rendered through pointillist acrylic painting, using the same colors as the upper part to bring unity to the picture. After passing through digital painting, this series enters another reincarnation in the genre of collage, drawing out the digital aesthetic of pixels through pointillism and a VHS aesthetic through the acrylic sticks — carrying forward the identity of the earlier digital-painting stage.\n \n"Music"\n \nThe <SIM_Visibility: The Visibility of Purgatory> series is composed entirely of works inspired by music. Music has no form; it is stored as digital files through recording. Yet through such formless digital data, listeners summon and hold their own memories and feelings.\nIn the same way, this series — through rhythmic images that have no figurative form, like a kind of digital pixel — visually conveys the uncertain visibility of the afterlife to the viewer, allowing each person to encounter their own afterlife and another image of life.',
