      "Around the area where mounds of red ochre earth are piled, fences block all human entry. Compared to when I used to pass by here, the look of the neighborhood where people once lived is now devastated beyond words. Around the heaps of collapsed houses, with no human presence, only a nameplate of someone who used to live here hangs forlornly.\nAll the people must have left for somewhere. The traces of the past lived here will be buried in time, and in the name of development and modernization that place will be filled with new spaces and new things.\nWhether it is the meaning of being to fade into the memories of the past once one's allotted lifespan is exhausted, I cannot say; but time will erase yesterday's forms and traces and transform that ground into yet another shape.\nThis work points to the things around us that are reduced to refuse, discarded and left to rot. Like branches of a tree torn up by the roots from a heap of upturned earth, they are old things that have lost their life and been thrown away.\nIn a materialist world, people indulge pathologically in the new and despise the old. The logic that the country's economy will revive and grow rich only by throwing away more and producing still more makes a mockery of the old memory of frugal, thrifty living.\nRecalling the things that disappear into the memories of the past, I think about what we lose and what we gain in this world that has supposedly grown better.",
