    title_en: 'Serenity Fortress',
    description_en:
      'In a state of deep absorption, the artist repeatedly draws and erases lines, building up a formal image. \nShe calls this image, formed between necessity and chance, a "fortress," and invites viewers inside.\nThrough the repetition and immersion of the working process, she dissolves inner conflict and instability — a condition tied to the precarious reality of the worker. Drawing inspiration from nature, she finds clues for her practice in the way animals, plants, and insects build their own fortresses to survive. Their methods of camouflage, concealment, and adaptation echo the artist\'s formal exploration.\n\nWorking on the basis of the afterimage of light, she gives it form through the line. The fortress is at once a space of self-protection and part of a journey toward an ideal. Through the work, she experiences an incomplete world, and through the repeated act of the line falls into a state of selflessness.\n\nThe forms that emerge as lines overlap reflect the artist\'s visual and psychological experience. They achieve formal variations that are at once simple and complex, and extend into natural patterns and into psychological imagery. Cacti, coral, clouds, waves, forests, mountain ranges — all kinds of natural forms appear on the canvas, and in that process a formal world unfolds where necessity and chance cross.',
