    title_en: 'Serenity Fortress',
    description_en:
      "In a state of deep absorption, I draw lines in regular patterns and repeat the act of opening\nand layering, building up a single sculptural image. The artist calls these worlds of imagery,\nfirmly built between the necessary and the contingent, a 'fortress,' and invites the viewer in.\n\nIn the working process, I emphasize the ideas of repetition and immersion, and through them\nI work through my own inner conflict and instability. This was something I had to take in—\nthe phenomena born of light's afterimage from past unstable experiences and visual trauma.\nI define myself as a 'precariat' and tie the reality of an unstable laborer to the act of working.\nThis instability operates as a defining element of life in both material foundation\nand psychological territory.\n\nInspiration drawn from the scenery of nature and from moving creatures gives me a sense\nof stability and imagination, and through it I hold many inner images. As I observe the nature\naround me, I find myself focusing on how the animals, plants, insects, and small creatures,\nin keeping with their living conditions, take just one of nature's materials and build a fortress\nof their own. Their own particular camouflage and concealment—their ability to build a safe\nfortress fitted to their own environment, and to live and adapt within it.\n\nAll of their processes are ways of surviving by protecting themselves. A fortress is at once\nmy own space for keeping myself firmly intact, and the place toward which I move,\ntoward an important goal of reaching an ideal. I, too, in the course of a life that requires\na fortress to live within, gather the materials of afterimages drawn through light and give them\nthe form of lines, building them into the work. My fortress is not yet complete; with the wish\nthat it will become, little by little, more solid and firm, it is an unfinished fortress\nadvancing toward the light.\n\n—from the artist's notes\nThe act of repeatedly drawing lines shows me, who cannot see the world incompletely.\nWhile so absorbed, I fall into a nameless state of self-loss. As lines are drawn and filled in,\na new world that cannot be defined appears on the canvas. This world reveals me, who has\nno choice but to see the world differently from others.\nThe forms that emerge through these utterly simple yet repetitive movements look like\nthe path of seeking that leads me toward myself. Through line-drawing, or line-tracing,\nI explore the sculptural variations of repeated labor. As countless moments of choice\naccumulate along the boundary between the necessary and the contingent, the resulting\n'pattern of lines' shifts into the inscrutable images of nature—cactus, undersea coral, clouds,\nwaves, forests, mountain ranges—or into imagery, the unfixed mental image.",
